      "thumb": "https://cdn.bsky.app/img/feed_thumbnail/plain/did:plc:ccxl3ictrlvtrrgh5swvvg47/bafkreibsv77g5zvxq4fpnijnrz36x73nsjbgz2rjph3lpxqn6uipzwy4dy",
      "fullsize": "https://cdn.bsky.app/img/feed_fullsize/plain/did:plc:ccxl3ictrlvtrrgh5swvvg47/bafkreibsv77g5zvxq4fpnijnrz36x73nsjbgz2rjph3lpxqn6uipzwy4dy",
      "alt": "Suppose your posterior barely moves despite what others consider strong evidence. There are two broad possibilities:\n\n1. Your prior odds are very different from theirs.\n\n2. Your likelihood ratio calibration is different-you assign a much smaller Bayes factor to the evidence.\n\nThese get conflated all the time.\n\nFor example:\n\nPrior odds: 1000:1 against.\n\nThey think the evidence has LR = 10,000.\n\nYou think the evidence has LR = 3.\n\nThen:\n\nTheir posterior becomes roughly 10:1 in favor. Yours becomes roughly 333:1 against.",
